-- Emcore, Freeport-McMoRan, Molycorp, Tesoro: U.S. Equity Movers
-- B y   K a t i a   P o r z e c a n s k i
-- 2011-12-28T22:41:21Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-27/anacor-pharmaceuticals-cavium-validus-u-s-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in U.S. trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of 4 p.m. in New York.  Oil refiners fell as the price of crude declined for the
first time in seven days.  Tesoro Corp. (TSO)   dropped 4.2 percent, the second-
biggest decline on the Standard and Poor’s 500 Index, to $23.07.
 Nabors Industries Ltd. (NBR)   fell 4.1 percent to $17.41.
 Weatherford International Ltd. (WFT)   retreated 3.9 percent to
$13.83.  Gold producers declined as the precious metal dropped for a
fifth straight session, the longest losing streak since October
2009, on prospects for slower demand in India and  China , the
world’s biggest consumers of bullion.  Freeport-McMoRan Copper & Gold Inc. (FCX)   fell 4.1
percent to $36.31.  Barrick Gold Corp. (ABX)   fell 2.8 percent
to $44.24.  Yamana Gold Inc. (YRI)   fell 3.8 percent to $14.22.  Arctic Cat Inc. (ACAT)   climbed 21 percent to $22.93, the
highest price since April 2006. The snowmobile maker reported a
cash buyback of 6.1 million Class B shares from Suzuki Motor
Corp.  Emcore Corp. (EMKR)   gained 6.4 percent, the most since
Dec. 9, to 92 cents. The solar-power company projected first-
quarter revenue of $36 million to $38 million and said it has
made agreements that allow the company to improve its liquidity
position while processing and receiving insurance claims related
to this year’s floods in  Thailand .  Endeavour International Corp. (END)   rose 12 percent to
$8.91, the highest price since Oct. 31. The Houston-based oil
and gas exploration company was raised to “market outperform”
from “market perform” at Rodman & Renshaw Capital Group Inc.
The price estimate is $12.50 a share.  Molycorp Inc. (MCP)   slumped 14 percent, the biggest
decline in the Russell 1000 Index, to $24.04. The price estimate
for the owner of the largest rare-earth deposit outside China
was cut to $39 a share from $57 by JPMorgan Chase & Co., which
cited pressure on rare earth prices.  To contact the reporter on this story:
